### Describe the bug

A contentConverter defined via the @JsonDeserialize annotation on an Enum Set field is ignored. 
Instead, Jackson always uses the built-in EnumSetDeserializer.

### Version Information

3.1.0

### Reproduction

```java
package org.example;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonCreator;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonProperty;
import java.time.DayOfWeek;
import java.util.Set;
import tools.jackson.databind.annotation.JsonDeserialize;
import tools.jackson.databind.json.JsonMapper;
import tools.jackson.databind.util.StdConverter;

public class Main {

    static void main() {
        var jsonMapper = JsonMapper.builder().build();

        //Day of week 3, Wednesday
        var json = "{\"weekDays\": [3]}";
        var example = jsonMapper.readValue(json, Example.class);
        //Prints Thursday which is the enum value at index 3
        IO.println(example.getWeekDays());
    }
}

class Example {

    @JsonCreator
    Example( @JsonProperty("weekDays") Set<DayOfWeek> weekDays) {
        this.weekDays = weekDays;
    }

    @JsonDeserialize(contentConverter = IntegerToDayOfWeekConverter.class)
    private final Set<DayOfWeek> weekDays;

    public Set<DayOfWeek> getWeekDays() {
        return weekDays;
    }
}

class IntegerToDayOfWeekConverter extends StdConverter<Integer, DayOfWeek> {

    @Override
    public DayOfWeek convert(Integer value) {
        return DayOfWeek.of(value);
    }
}
``` 


### Expected behavior

The converter defined in the @JsonDeserialize annotation is used

