When using @JsonIdentityInfo (with StringIdGenerator) together with @JsonTypeInfo / @JsonSubTypes and builder-based deserialization (@JsonDeserialize(builder=...)), back-references to already-deserialized objects fail with:

     UnresolvedForwardReference: Unresolved forward references: [{Object id: "id1"}]

This appears to be because the Object Id gets registered against the builder instance rather than the final built object, so when a subsequent reference tries to resolve the id, the lookup fails.

The failure is specifically tied to builder-based deserialization combined with polymorphic type info and object identity — regardless of whether the base type is a class or interface.

To reproduce:

```java
  @JsonTypeInfo(use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME)
  @JsonSubTypes({@JsonSubTypes.Type(name = "Derived", value = Derived.class)})
  @JsonIdentityInfo(generator = ObjectIdGenerators.StringIdGenerator.class,
          resolver = SimpleObjectIdResolver.class)
  interface Base { }

  @JsonDeserialize(builder = Derived.DerivedBuilder.class)
  class Derived implements Base {
      public String a;
      Derived(String a) { this.a = a; }

      @JsonPOJOBuilder(withPrefix = "", buildMethodName = "build")
      static class DerivedBuilder {
          private String a;
          public DerivedBuilder a(String a) { this.a = a; return this; }
          public Derived build() { return new Derived(this.a); }
      }
  }

  // Second list element references the first by id — fails
  String json = """
      {"list":[
          {"@type":"Derived","@id":"id1","a":"foo"},
          "id1"
      ]}""";
```

### Describe the bug

`EnumMapDeserializer.createContextual()` and `EnumSetDeserializer.createContextual()` do not call `findConvertingContentDeserializer()`.
As a result, property-level `@JsonDeserialize(contentConverter = ...)` is not applied for `EnumMap` values or `EnumSet` elements.

Peer deserializers already apply this hook during contextualization, including:
- `MapDeserializer`
- `CollectionDeserializer`
- `ObjectArrayDeserializer`
- `StringArrayDeserializer`
- `StringCollectionDeserializer`
- `ReferenceTypeDeserializer` (see #4339)

### Version

Reproduced on `3.x` HEAD.
The same contextualization gap also exists in `2.x` code.

### To reproduce

```java
static class PointConverter extends StdConverter<int[], Point> {
    @Override
    public Point convert(int[] value) {
        return new Point(value[0], value[1]);
    }
}

static class EnumMapWrapper {
    @JsonDeserialize(contentConverter = PointConverter.class)
    public EnumMap<MyEnum, Point> values;
}

mapper.readValue("{\"values\":{\"A\":[1,2]}}", EnumMapWrapper.class);
```

This fails with `MismatchedInputException` because the converter is never applied.

`EnumSet` fails analogously when a property-level `contentConverter` is used for elements.

### Expected behavior

`contentConverter` should be applied to `EnumMap` values and `EnumSet` elements, consistent with other container deserializers.

### Additional context

This looks like the same kind of specialized-path gap that was fixed for `ReferenceTypeDeserializer` in #4337 / #4339.

I locally verified that adding one `findConvertingContentDeserializer()` call in each `createContextual()` method fixes both cases and can be covered with focused regression tests.

